my staff on that, you know.

444
00:25:21,760 --> 00:25:23,800
Uh, staff, what hotel
are we staying at?

445
00:25:23,880 --> 00:25:26,240
- You book the hotel?
- No. Talk to him.

446
00:25:26,320 --> 00:25:28,320
- You book the hotel?
- What hotel?

447
00:25:28,400 --> 00:25:31,440
Nobody told me
about no damn hotel.

448
00:25:31,520 --> 00:25:33,920
Uh, is, uh, staff...

449
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:38,200
obviously failed to nail
some vital details, so...

450
00:25:38,280 --> 00:25:41,120
Oh, geez,
the world bank's in town.

451
00:25:41,200 --> 00:25:43,160
Where we gonna find you a room?

452
00:25:44,200 --> 00:25:46,080
Hey, I kick your ass.

453
00:25:48,080 --> 00:25:50,960
You have to be firm
with the staff sometimes.

454
00:25:51,040 --> 00:25:55,240
[P.A. Announcer] Continental
flight 228 to Chicago O'Hare is now...

455
00:25:55,280 --> 00:25:57,400
I got lucky at the Hay-Adams.

456
00:25:57,480 --> 00:26:00,400
- There was a coup in Uruguay.
-  Que?

457
00:26:00,480 --> 00:26:03,640
- What?
- Uruguay.

458
00:26:03,720 --> 00:26:05,600
Anyway, their delegation
just checked out.

459
00:26:05,680 --> 00:26:08,440
You're a wizard, Reinhardt, and I knew
we could count on you. Let's go.

460
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:10,360
- Hey, you got that?
- Yes, sir.

461
00:26:10,440 --> 00:26:12,320
[Loretta]
Careful with that bag.

462
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:14,480
Don't throw it in there like that.
I paid too much for that bag.

463
00:26:14,560 --> 00:26:16,280
- Say, Congressman?
- Yo.

464
00:26:16,360 --> 00:26:18,920
I'd like to ask you something.

465
00:26:18,960 --> 00:26:23,320
I would appreciate it if you
would consider me to be your A.A.

466
00:26:23,400 --> 00:26:27,080
Oh, that's very nice of you.
That's a very decent gesture.

467
00:26:27,120 --> 00:26:29,800
But yo, man, listen.
I'm a social drinker.

468
00:26:29,880 --> 00:26:33,080
I don't really hit
the bottle very much.

469
00:26:33,160 --> 00:26:35,480
Yeah, yeah. No, no. Uh,

470
00:26:35,560 --> 00:26:37,560
administrative assistant.

471
00:26:37,640 --> 00:26:40,800
- Oh!
- As you know, I used to work
for Congressman Johnson.

472
00:26:40,840 --> 00:26:44,560
And I would like to work for you,
Congressman Johnson.

473
00:26:46,280 --> 00:26:49,880
So it would be sorta like an affirmative
action sorta thing. [Chuckles]

474
00:26:49,960 --> 00:26:52,480
Only kidding. I got your resume.
I'll call you, okay?

475
00:26:52,520 --> 00:26:55,840
- I'll look forward to hearing from you?
- Look forward to talking to you.

476
00:27:14,720 --> 00:27:16,680
[Giddy Chuckle]

477
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:23,400
Ooh, baby!

478
00:27:32,080 --> 00:27:34,440
[Secretary]
Congressman Corman's office.

479
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:45,720
Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

480
00:27:45,800 --> 00:27:47,880
[Chuckling]

481
00:27:49,240 --> 00:27:51,160
[Elevator Bell Rings]

482
00:27:53,520 --> 00:27:56,840
- Members only.
- Oh, we're going up to
Congressman Johnson's office.

483
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:59,560
I hate to be the one to tell you,
but Congressman Johnson died.

484
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:05,120
I'm the new congressman. I'm Congressman
Johnson and this is my staff.

485
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:07,880
I'm sorry, Congressman.
I didn't see your pin.

486
00:28:07,920 --> 00:28:11,480
In fact, I still
don't see your pin.

487
00:28:11,560 --> 00:28:14,360
- What pin?
- Your member-of-Congress pin.

488
00:28:16,440 --> 00:28:21,000
- I'm gonna have to look you up.
- I'm in the book under Johnson.
Thomas Johnson.

489
00:28:21,040 --> 00:28:23,560
- Congressman.
- [Giggling]

490
00:28:23,640 --> 00:28:25,960
Thomas Jefferson Johnson.

491
00:28:26,040 --> 00:28:29,400
- Yeah, I'm the man.
- No picture available.

492
00:28:29,480 --> 00:28:34,200
Oh, wait a second. I have my driver's
license with me. Got a picture in late.

493
00:28:34,280 --> 00:28:36,520
Here it...
If I can get it out.

494
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:40,760
- Driver's license.
- Oh.

495
00:28:42,040 --> 00:28:45,280
See? Same cat.

496
00:28:45,360 --> 00:28:48,840
How could I ever have doubted you?
Where to?

497
00:28:48,880 --> 00:28:50,720
We're going up to 518.

498
00:28:50,760 --> 00:28:53,920
Well, the elevator
only goes to four. You'll have
to take the stairs from there.

499
00:28:57,480 --> 00:29:00,800
Are you gonna be grabbin' my ass
like old Congressman Johnson?

500
00:29:00,840 --> 00:29:03,280
Oh, no. I would
never grab your ass.

501
00:29:03,360 --> 00:29:06,640
Well, you said that awful fast.
What's wrong with my ass?

502
00:29:06,720 --> 00:29:08,640
Oh, there's nothing
wrong with your ass.

503
00:29:08,720 --> 00:29:11,640
I'm just, you know, I'm just, what,
I'm, I'm the new congressman,

504
00:29:11,720 --> 00:29:14,200
and I won't be doin' none
of those things he did.

505
00:29:14,280 --> 00:29:17,680
I ain't gonna grab nobody's old ass.
I mean, I ain't gonna grab nobody's ass.

506
00:29:17,760 --> 00:29:20,360
You know? Hey, I think we
on the fourth floor.

507
00:29:20,440 --> 00:29:23,000
I'll grab it.

508
00:29:24,520 --> 00:29:26,680
[Elevator Bell Ringing]

509
00:29:27,800 --> 00:29:30,760
Stairs are to the right.
Enjoy.

510
00:29:33,800 --> 00:29:35,640
Later, baby.

511
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:15,920
Wait here a second.

512
00:30:22,920 --> 00:30:25,640
Good morning, Congressman.

513
00:30:25,680 --> 00:30:29,120
What is this shit-hole?
Look at this place. What is this?

514
00:30:29,200 --> 00:30:33,800
Oh, um... you missed
the freshman lottery for offices.

515
00:30:33,880 --> 00:30:35,880
They assign them by draw.

516
00:30:35,960 --> 00:30:40,040
You didn't show for the draw,
so you got the worst office in Congress.

517
00:30:40,080 --> 00:30:41,800
What lottery?
I missed a lottery?

518
00:30:41,840 --> 00:30:45,080
It was all in those briefing books
I mailed you.

519
00:30:47,880 --> 00:30:50,240
What else have we missed here?

520
00:30:50,320 --> 00:30:52,960
Are you hiring me, Congressman?

521
00:30:54,200 --> 00:30:56,520
- It's a shakedown.
- Excuse me?

522
00:30:56,560 --> 00:31:00,400
Oh, ho-ho-ho! You're shaking
me down, aren't you?

523
00:31:00,480 --> 00:31:02,400
Okay, I'm gonna love this town.

524
00:31:02,480 --> 00:31:05,720
Okay, I've been here five minutes
and you're already shaking me down.

525
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:07,640
All right, you're hired.

526
00:31:07,720 --> 00:31:11,200
Listen, fill me in on everything
'cause I don't wanna miss the good shit.

527
00:31:11,240 --> 00:31:16,000
## [Classical]

528
00:31:21,520 --> 00:31:24,040
[Indistinct Chatter]

529
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:29,480
- Let's go meet the natives.
- Yeah.

530
00:31:29,520 --> 00:31:32,920
[Thomas] Can you be
a little more elegant than that?

531
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:34,920
Shakin' your ass and shit.

532
00:31:38,440 --> 00:31:40,920
Hey, how ya doin'?
Thomas Johnson.

533
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:44,040
Rafe Simon, freshman from Tulsa.
And this is...

534
00:31:44,120 --> 00:31:47,400
- Bo Chandler from, uh...
- Lufkin, Texas.

535
00:31:47,440 --> 00:31:49,920
Great party.

536
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:53,160
You're Jeff Johnson,
the guy from Florida.

537
00:31:53,200 --> 00:31:54,880
Yeah, that's me.

538
00:31:54,960 --> 00:31:58,160
You know, the rest of us were
out there on the campaign trail,

539
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:02,920
raising money, kissing ass,
making speeches, dragging
our butts from place to place.

540
00:32:02,960 --> 00:32:05,000
And he slides in
on pure name recognition.

541
00:32:06,640 --> 00:32:09,680
Let me tell you something, Jeff.

542
00:32:09,760 --> 00:32:11,600
Fuckin' brilliant!

543
00:32:13,640 --> 00:32:17,440
I thought I was gonna have to kick
somebody's... Okay. Hey, no, I'm sorry.

544
00:32:17,480 --> 00:32:19,520
Thanks a lot.
And don't call me Jeff.

545
00:32:19,600 --> 00:32:22,760
Jeff is my working name.
My name is Thomas, and this
is my cousin, Miss Loretta.

546
00:32:22,840 --> 00:32:27,400
How do you do? How do you do?
[Laughing]

547
00:32:27,440 --> 00:32:29,440
What were you guys before you
got elected? Lawyers or something?

548
00:32:29,520 --> 00:32:33,280
Oh, hey, no. I did morning weather
and traffic for KTOK in Tulsa.

549
00:32:33,360 --> 00:32:35,680
- Oh. [Laughing]
- [Chandler] You don't remember me?

550
00:32:35,760 --> 00:32:38,600
Tight end for the Oilers?
My knee gimped out on me?

551
00:32:38,640 --> 00:32:42,680
Oh, yes! Oh, hey, man.
I was wonderin' what happened to you.

552
00:32:42,760 --> 00:32:45,080
- Why don't you stop by my reception?
- Yeah, but don't go...

553
00:32:45,160 --> 00:32:46,880
to his reception before
you go to my reception.

554
00:32:46,960 --> 00:32:49,320
I'm gonna be offended
if you don't come by my reception.

555
00:32:49,360 --> 00:32:51,240
- Okay.
- [Thomas] Okay.

556
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:53,600
I guess you're gonna
have to have a reception.

557
00:32:53,680 --> 00:32:55,520
Yes, I guess we'll have
to have something.

558
00:32:55,600 --> 00:32:58,280
Shit, I don't know nothin'
about no reception.

559
00:32:58,320 --> 00:33:01,280
You know what I love about this town?
The way everybody call you a member.

560
00:33:01,320 --> 00:33:04,200
Every time I hear that,
it make me think about Mister Happy.

561
00:33:04,280 --> 00:33:06,640
- [Laughing]
- Hey, hey!

562
00:33:06,680 --> 00:33:10,280
Watch them sprinklets, man! He's
laughin' and piss shootin' everyplace.

563
00:33:10,320 --> 00:33:12,840
I got a sprinkler too now.
Back at ya!

564
00:33:12,920 --> 00:33:14,360
- Ow!
- All right, then.

565
00:33:15,760 --> 00:33:18,320
- Mike Hoyt, lowa.
- Thomas Johnson, Florida.

566
00:33:18,400 --> 00:33:22,200
So how'd you wind up in D.C., lowa?
You do the crop report
on TV or somethin'?

567
00:33:22,280 --> 00:33:24,480
No, actually, I owe it all
to the Vietnamese.

568
00:33:24,520 --> 00:33:26,440
Oh, you're a war hero.

569
00:33:26,520 --> 00:33:28,880
P.O.W. When I got back
to Cedar Rapids,

570
00:33:28,920 --> 00:33:32,360
I spent so many years telling the Rotary
Club what was wrong in Washington...

571
00:33:32,400 --> 00:33:35,080
they finally told me to either
put up or shut up. Ha!

572
00:33:35,160 --> 00:33:37,080
So I put up, and here I am.

573
00:33:37,160 --> 00:33:40,360
What are you talkin' about?
What's wrong with Washington?
Washington's great!

574
00:33:40,440 --> 00:33:43,520
Oh, come on. We got acid rain
killing fish and nobody's stopping it.

575
00:33:43,600 --> 00:33:45,960
There's topsoil being washed away.
No erosion programs.

576
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:48,840
- Why, there's chemicals
in the livestock that...
- We might have some luck.

577
00:33:48,880 --> 00:33:51,840
My God, I sound like a boy scout.
[Laughing]

578
00:33:51,880 --> 00:33:55,840
No, actually, that's nice. This town
could use a few geeks like you.

579
00:33:58,360 --> 00:34:01,040
- Hi.
- Pete Slocum, Asbestos
Information Institute.

580
00:34:01,120 --> 00:34:02,960
How are ya, Pete?
Nice to meet ya.

581
00:34:03,040 --> 00:34:05,000
Ken Korngold, National
Distilled Spirits Association.

582
00:34:05,080 --> 00:34:07,080
- Very good to meet you, Ken.
- Nice to meet you.

583
00:34:07,160 --> 00:34:10,120
- Paul Zeckhauser, American
Tobacco Council. [Coughing]
- How are you, Paul?

584
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:13,600
I hope you can all come to my reception.
You know Miss Loretta from my office.

585
00:34:13,640 --> 00:34:15,640
- Hi. Hello.
- Terry Corrigan.

586
00:34:15,720 --> 00:34:20,440
Soon as I saw how you got elected,
I knew you were a real comer.

587
00:34:20,520 --> 00:34:23,000
Hell, I bet Olaf Andersen
voted for you.

588
00:34:23,080 --> 00:34:24,880
I don't know.
Who's Olaf Andersen?

589
00:34:24,920 --> 00:34:27,640
Won't tell him you asked.
Fella on the left up there.

590
00:34:27,720 --> 00:34:29,480
Chairman, Gulf Coast Power.

591
00:34:29,520 --> 00:34:32,040
Constituent of yours,
client of mine.

592
00:34:32,120 --> 00:34:34,120
Pays the rent,
know what I mean?

593
00:34:34,200 --> 00:34:37,160
Say, could I host a "welcome
to Washington" fund-raiser for you,

594
00:34:37,240 --> 00:34:39,200
down at my law firm
on K Street?

595
00:34:39,280 --> 00:34:42,760
- Absolutely.
- At $500 a head,

596
00:34:42,840 --> 00:34:46,160
you could pick up 20, 25 grand
to help you get started.

597
00:34:46,240 --> 00:34:48,160
[Nervous Laugh]

598
00:34:48,240 --> 00:34:50,240
And how much of that
are you gonna get?

599
00:34:50,320 --> 00:34:52,280
It doesn't come off the top.

600
00:34:52,360 --> 00:34:56,800
Down the road,
I'll bill each of them 500 an hour
whenever I take you to lunch.

601
00:34:59,600 --> 00:35:02,280
You know, Terry, you and I
are gonna be so close.

602
00:35:04,760 --> 00:35:07,480
I wanna welcome
the new members to Washington.

603
00:35:12,280 --> 00:35:14,920
We haven't had a freshman class
this big in a long time.

604
00:35:14,960 --> 00:35:17,320
[Laughing]

605
00:35:17,360 --> 00:35:21,120
Well, Congress needs your new blood, and
you in turn are gonna need new friends.

606
00:35:21,200 --> 00:35:25,480
That's why, tonight, we unite
the two great pillars of our system.

607
00:35:25,520 --> 00:35:27,520
Political and financial.

608
00:35:27,600 --> 00:35:30,920
Now, you know, Congress
has taken many hits of late.

609
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:32,800
But, Congressmen,
look around you.

610
00:35:32,840 --> 00:35:37,600
The people you see here tonight
are the ones that have stood behind us.

611
00:35:37,680 --> 00:35:41,600
And they are the ones that will be
invaluable to you in your next campaign,

612
00:35:41,680 --> 00:35:44,480
which I might remind you
is less than two years away.

613
00:35:44,520 --> 00:35:49,160
Now this is our system of checks
and balances at its very finest.

614
00:35:49,240 --> 00:35:53,120
Dick Dodge, from your home state.
Gonna run for speaker.

615
00:35:53,160 --> 00:35:55,720
Raises more money
than any other member.

616
00:35:55,760 --> 00:35:58,120
But, of course,
he's on the right committee,

617
00:35:58,160 --> 00:36:01,120
- Which makes all the difference.
- Yeah, of course.

618
00:36:01,160 --> 00:36:03,840
But I'm not telling you anything
you don't already know.

619
00:36:03,920 --> 00:36:08,560
No, he's on the right committee, so
I guess that makes all the difference.

620
00:36:08,640 --> 00:36:13,320
Not just on the committee.
He's chairman of it.

621
00:36:13,400 --> 00:36:16,720
The big boys have to line up
to take numbers...

622
00:36:16,800 --> 00:36:18,720
to throw money his way.

623
00:36:18,800 --> 00:36:22,600
- Your friends can always call on you.
- No shit.

624
00:36:22,640 --> 00:36:24,680
[Woman]
Thank you very much.

625
00:36:24,760 --> 00:36:27,080
[Dodge]
Oh, uh, Mr. Johnson?

626
00:36:27,120 --> 00:36:29,080
You know, it's customary
for the new members...

627
00:36:29,160 --> 00:36:33,400
to pay a visit on us old fogies
in the leadership, especially
from your home state.

628
00:36:33,480 --> 00:36:36,480
Well, I would have, but I
just got in town. I'm sorry, man.

629
00:36:36,520 --> 00:36:39,040
You know, you can make up for it
by having a nightcap with me.

630
00:36:39,080 --> 00:36:42,680
- Oh, absolutely.
- Can I have my car take you home?

631
00:36:47,520 --> 00:36:49,440
Uh, excuse me, Mr. Chairman,

632
00:36:49,520 --> 00:36:52,800
but you ain't about to start no homo
shit, are you? 'Cause I ain't with it.

633
00:36:52,840 --> 00:36:55,080
- Oh?
- Hey.

634
00:36:55,160 --> 00:36:59,400
No! But that's good thinking, Thomas.
I'm impressed by your instincts.

635
00:36:59,440 --> 00:37:01,640
I didn't wanna
have to whup your ass.

636
00:37:01,720 --> 00:37:03,800
- [Laughing]
- You know what I mean?

637
00:37:17,440 --> 00:37:21,240
Tell me, Mr. Johnson,
why'd you come to Washington?

638
00:37:22,920 --> 00:37:26,440
Well, of course, it's an opportunity
to do something for my country, and...

639
00:37:26,480 --> 00:37:28,760
Now let's just cut the bullshit.

640
00:37:28,840 --> 00:37:30,680
I saw how you got elected.

641
00:37:30,760 --> 00:37:33,600
Now flukes like you are either
nut cases or troublemakers.

642
00:37:33,640 --> 00:37:36,960
I just wanna know which one
I've got on my hands.

643
00:37:37,040 --> 00:37:38,880
Why did you run for Congress?

644
00:37:40,800 --> 00:37:43,200
- No bullshit?
- No bullshit.

645
00:37:43,240 --> 00:37:45,320
We got this whole
topsoil problem...

646
00:37:45,400 --> 00:37:48,360
and, uh, acid rain
is killing cattle.

647
00:37:48,440 --> 00:37:51,480
- [Pounding At Door]
- What? Yes? What? What?

648
00:37:51,560 --> 00:37:55,160
- What?
- [Thomas] Einhardt! Wake up!

649
00:37:55,240 --> 00:37:59,880
[Pounding Continues]

650
00:38:02,160 --> 00:38:04,840
What is the name of that committee
Dick Dodge is chairman of?

651
00:38:04,880 --> 00:38:07,200
- Congressman, this is a surprise.
- Come on, man, spit it out.

652
00:38:07,280 --> 00:38:09,800
- What's the name of the committee?
- Uh... Uh...

653
00:38:09,840 --> 00:38:11,840
Come on, come on, come on.
What is it?

654
00:38:11,920 --> 00:38:15,640
Uh... oh.
Power and Industry.

655
00:38:15,720 --> 00:38:17,560
- Is something wrong with the hotel?
- No.

656
00:38:17,640 --> 00:38:19,720
Tell me about this Power and Industry.
I heard it's really good.

657
00:38:19,760 --> 00:38:22,600
- This is a good thing, right?
- Yes, they call it "the honey pot."

658
00:38:22,680 --> 00:38:27,280
Each member is constantly being lobbied
by every cash-rich trade group in town.

659
00:38:27,360 --> 00:38:30,200
Oh, it's 2:40 a.m.
Did you realize that?

660
00:38:30,280 --> 00:38:32,880
Ah, man, forget that!
We're public servants.

661
00:38:32,960 --> 00:38:35,040
Time ain't supposed to mean
nothin' to us, right?

662
00:38:35,120 --> 00:38:38,600
- How do I get on this committee?
- Um, that would be seniority.

663
00:38:38,640 --> 00:38:41,600
Uh, after six terms in office,

664
00:38:41,680 --> 00:38:43,800
uh, say, 12 years of service,

665
00:38:43,880 --> 00:38:47,200
your name moves along the list
and before you know it,

666
00:38:47,280 --> 00:38:50,440
you're off the Fisheries committee
and on to Power and Industry.

667
00:38:50,480 --> 00:38:54,400
- Can this wait? I'm much
more coherent in the morning.
- No, you're doin' fine.

668
00:38:54,440 --> 00:38:58,120
But I need to know how I can get
on this committee, like, immediately.

669
00:38:58,160 --> 00:39:01,080
Okay, okay.
All right, all right.

670
00:39:01,160 --> 00:39:03,040
Uh, immediately. Immediately.

671
00:39:03,120 --> 00:39:06,320
- Within, say, your next four years?
- No, no, no, no.

672
00:39:06,360 --> 00:39:08,680
Immediately,
like in my first four days.

673
00:39:17,560 --> 00:39:19,880
Now you're a smart guy.
That's why I hired you.

674
00:39:19,960 --> 00:39:22,880
You might be standin' here
in these fire engine boxer shorts,

675
00:39:22,920 --> 00:39:25,720
but I have faith in you.
I'm countin' on you.

676
00:39:25,800 --> 00:39:27,480
- Talk to me, Reinhardt.
- Yes, thank you.

677
00:39:27,560 --> 00:39:29,440
I don't think
it's possible, sir.

678
00:39:29,480 --> 00:39:32,400
It would be unprecedented
for a freshman congressman...

679
00:39:32,480 --> 00:39:34,400
to be put onto that committee.

680
00:39:34,440 --> 00:39:36,280
Unless...

681
00:39:36,360 --> 00:39:39,560
Well, only in the most remote,

682
00:39:39,640 --> 00:39:42,280
hypo...
hypothetical situation.

683
00:39:42,360 --> 00:39:44,600
Yes?

684
00:39:44,680 --> 00:39:46,640
- This is ridiculous, right?
- For instance?

685
00:39:46,720 --> 00:39:50,440
Well, if the, uh, President
of the United States...

686
00:39:50,480 --> 00:39:52,880
were to do you a personal favor.

687
00:39:52,920 --> 00:39:56,320
Or, uh, some enormously powerful
special interest group.

688
00:39:56,400 --> 00:39:58,560
Chairman Dodge, please.

689
00:39:58,640 --> 00:40:03,200
Will you tell him that it's Mr. Joshua
Benjamin from the NAACP on the line?

690
00:40:06,760 --> 00:40:09,240
No, ma'am, actually, you'll
be of a great deal of help.

691
00:40:09,320 --> 00:40:11,920
I have a few minor questions.
I would like to know...

692
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:16,480
how many members of the chairman's
committee are African-Americans.

693
00:40:16,560 --> 00:40:21,120
None. Well, I'm sure you have
a Latino member on the committee.

694
00:40:21,200 --> 00:40:23,240
No Latinos either.

695
00:40:23,280 --> 00:40:28,040
Does the chairman have any Asians or
any Native Americans on the committee?

696
00:40:28,080 --> 00:40:30,440
No Asians and no natives.

697
00:40:30,480 --> 00:40:34,560
Does the chairman have any handicaps
or gays on the committee?

698
00:40:34,640 --> 00:40:38,200
No gays. Well, you've been
of a great deal of help.

699
00:40:38,280 --> 00:40:42,760
Just forget I even called.
Just tell him I said hi.

700
00:40:42,840 --> 00:40:46,680
Okay, um, Armando, Van Dyke,
you guys are up next.

701
00:40:46,760 --> 00:40:49,240
I'll go hit 'em with
the Urban League right away.

702
00:40:49,320 --> 00:40:54,280
Fine. And I'll be the conference of
Southern Baptist Bishops. [Chuckling]

703
00:40:54,360 --> 00:40:56,160
What do you want me to do?

704
00:40:58,920 --> 00:41:01,800
Oh, hi. We haven't met yet.

705
00:41:01,840 --> 00:41:04,320
I'm Loretta Hicks.
Congressman Johnson's office?

706
00:41:04,400 --> 00:41:07,880
Oh, hi. I'm Kimberly Meadows.
I work for Chairman Dodge.

707
00:41:07,960 --> 00:41:11,280
Power and Industry.
How'd you get that job?

708
00:41:11,360 --> 00:41:13,400
I used to serve under
the other Congressman Johnson,

709
00:41:13,480 --> 00:41:16,520
so I had the right experience.

710
00:41:16,600 --> 00:41:20,000
Well, I hope you haven't
been bothered by the pickets.

711
00:41:20,080 --> 00:41:22,440
What pickets?

712
00:41:22,480 --> 00:41:25,400
Oh. Did, did I let
the cat out of the bag?

713
00:41:25,480 --> 00:41:28,680
- Are we gonna be picketed?
- Look, you've got to promise...

714
00:41:28,720 --> 00:41:30,600
not to say where
you heard this from.

715
00:41:30,640 --> 00:41:32,880
- Not even my congressman knows.
- I promise.

716
00:41:32,960 --> 00:41:37,400
Okay. My boyfriend works
at the Rainbow Coalition,

717
00:41:37,480 --> 00:41:38,760
and he said...

718
00:41:38,840 --> 00:41:42,080
[Telephone Ringing]

719
00:41:42,160 --> 00:41:44,320
[Telephone Ringing]

720
00:41:44,360 --> 00:41:48,280
Congressman Johnson's office.
Chairman Dodge?

721
00:41:50,200 --> 00:41:53,000
Yes. Okay.

722
00:41:54,800 --> 00:41:56,840
That was Dodge.
He wants to see you pronto.

723
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:00,000
So we still haven't
lost our touch.

724
00:42:02,560 --> 00:42:04,760
Asi.

725
00:42:04,840 --> 00:42:07,560
He should be back in a moment,
Congressman Johnson.

726
00:42:07,640 --> 00:42:09,480
[Thomas]
Oh! They're here now.

727
00:42:09,560 --> 00:42:11,440
- We haven't met. Eli Hawkins.
- How ya doin'?

728
00:42:11,480 --> 00:42:14,000
Brother Eli. Yeah. All right.

729
00:42:14,080 --> 00:42:17,680
- All right. Thomas Johnson.
- Yes, I know. The Florida upset.

730
00:42:17,760 --> 00:42:20,320
Now that you're here,
what are you gonna do with it?

731
00:42:20,400 --> 00:42:24,040
You gonna feather your own nest, or are
you gonna make something of your office?

732
00:42:24,080 --> 00:42:28,200
Hey, I'm gonna be as good a congressmen
as anybody else up here, all right?

733
00:42:28,240 --> 00:42:30,160
Exactly what does that mean?

734
00:42:33,720 --> 00:42:36,400
Well, uh, ever since
I got back from, from 'Nam...

735
00:42:36,480 --> 00:42:39,240
I personally wanna do something
about the rain forests.

736
00:42:39,280 --> 00:42:42,600
Well, do me a favor. Don't tell me.
I've just had my lunch.

737
00:42:42,680 --> 00:42:46,480
Eli, you're gonna
have to excuse us. Thomas and I
are late for a meeting. Come on in.

738
00:42:46,560 --> 00:42:48,400
What's his problem?

739
00:42:52,360 --> 00:42:56,320
Uh, Mr. Chairman, I have been meaning
to ask your advice about something.

740
00:42:56,400 --> 00:42:59,120
I'm always available
to a young man from my state.

741
00:42:59,200 --> 00:43:01,320
Great. It's about
committee assignments.

742
00:43:01,400 --> 00:43:05,600
Now that's interesting. That's just
the thing I had in mind. Go ahead.

743
00:43:05,640 --> 00:43:08,280
For the last two days,
I have been getting approached...

744
00:43:08,360 --> 00:43:10,640
by a bunch of chairmen
from different committees.

745
00:43:10,720 --> 00:43:12,680
I've been approached by the people
from Foreign Affairs.

746
00:43:12,760 --> 00:43:15,920
I've been approached by the people
from Ways and Means and Armed Services.

747
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:18,120
They all want me on their committees
and I don't know why.

748
00:43:18,160 --> 00:43:21,480
- I'll be damned!
- You can understand my dilemma,
'cause it's like,

749
00:43:21,520 --> 00:43:24,720
with Foreign Affairs, you get to
fly off to Paris whenever you want.

750
00:43:24,800 --> 00:43:27,600
With Armed Services,
they got bases all over the globe.

751
00:43:27,680 --> 00:43:30,640
Son, are you familiar with
my committee? Power and Industry?

752
00:43:30,720 --> 00:43:34,760
Oh, yeah. But, uh, it's not as well
known as these other committees.

753
00:43:34,800 --> 00:43:38,520
Well, maybe not, but you've
been very frank with me.

754
00:43:38,600 --> 00:43:41,360
I'm gonna be
extremely frank with you.

755
00:43:41,440 --> 00:43:44,640
These other committees,
they're nickel-and-dime stuff.

756
00:43:44,680 --> 00:43:47,200
Power and Industry,
think of what we cover.

757
00:43:47,280 --> 00:43:51,560
Energy, transportation,
insurance, the environment.

758
00:43:51,640 --> 00:43:54,280
Hell, son, there's no better
committee on the Hill.

759
00:43:54,320 --> 00:43:57,160
That is, if you're interested
in fund-raising.

760
00:43:57,200 --> 00:44:00,960
I am, very much. It's just that these
other chairmen made pretty strong cases.

761
00:44:01,040 --> 00:44:03,120
These other chairmen
aren't from your home state.

762
00:44:03,200 --> 00:44:04,960
Hmm.

763
00:44:05,040 --> 00:44:07,760
They're not offering
to take you under their wing.

764
00:44:07,840 --> 00:44:11,680
- Look out for your future.
- And you are?

765
00:44:11,760 --> 00:44:13,720
Hell yes, I am.

766
00:44:13,800 --> 00:44:16,160
Oh, well, I'm very flattered,
Mr. Chairman.

767
00:44:16,240 --> 00:44:17,640
Dick.

768
00:44:17,680 --> 00:44:20,840
- Well, I'm very flattered, Mr. Dick.
- No, no, no, no.

769
00:44:20,880 --> 00:44:23,560
- Oh, I'm sorry, Chairman Dick.
- No, Dick. Just Dick.

770
00:44:23,600 --> 00:44:25,480
- Oh, Dick. Just plain old Dick.
- Yeah.

771
00:44:25,520 --> 00:44:29,520
Fine. I know you don't
get something for nothing.
What do you want from me, Dick?

772
00:44:29,600 --> 00:44:33,480
[Chuckles] Well, son,
I want an able lieutenant.

773
00:44:34,920 --> 00:44:37,920
And I want you to smile
for the cameras.

774
00:44:40,240 --> 00:44:43,320
Skeeter, you know Thomas Johnson,
the new member of the committee?

775
00:44:43,400 --> 00:44:45,440
Thomas, this is
Barclay Warburton.

776
00:44:45,520 --> 00:44:47,800
- How are you, Barclay?
- Skeeter, please.

777
00:44:47,880 --> 00:44:50,920
- Been called that since boarding school.
- Oh, sorry, man.

778
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:53,800
- Cheers.
- Yeah, cheers. Skeeter.

779
00:44:53,880 --> 00:44:56,640
Thomas, please. Been called that
since reform school.

780
00:45:02,280 --> 00:45:06,640
This EPA oversight hearing
of the committee on Power
and Industry will come to order.

781
00:45:06,720 --> 00:45:09,960
I would like to welcome
our first witness,

782
00:45:10,040 --> 00:45:13,480
the distinguished administrator
of the Environmental Protection Agency.

783
00:45:13,560 --> 00:45:17,760
But before I do,
I would like to note that we
have a new member joining us today.

784
00:45:17,840 --> 00:45:19,680
The distinguished gentleman
from Florida.

785
00:45:22,480 --> 00:45:25,960
[Photographer] Congressman Johnson?
Sir, can we get a shot, please?

786
00:45:26,040 --> 00:45:28,520
- Thank you.
- How am I doing?

787
00:45:28,600 --> 00:45:30,400
Great. Great.

788
00:45:31,840 --> 00:45:34,080
Well, Mike, enjoy
those hors d'oeuvres.

789
00:45:34,120 --> 00:45:39,080
[Indistinct Chatter]

790
00:45:40,240 --> 00:45:42,920
Hi. My name is Miss Loretta,
and I'd like it...

791
00:45:42,960 --> 00:45:46,400
very much if you'd sign
one of these little name tags.

792
00:45:46,440 --> 00:45:48,360
That would be just nice.

793
00:45:48,400 --> 00:45:52,640
It's an informal breakfast. You give us
your point of view, we give you, uh,

794
00:45:52,720 --> 00:45:55,200
bacon and eggs
plus a $2,000 honorarium.

795
00:45:55,280 --> 00:45:57,600
For your favorite charity,
of course.

796
00:45:57,680 --> 00:46:01,160
The Thomas Jefferson Johnson
Foundation.

797
00:46:01,240 --> 00:46:03,840
Oh, okay. An honorarium.

798
00:46:03,920 --> 00:46:05,800
I like the way that sounds.

799
00:46:05,960 --> 00:46:07,600
[Man] Excuse me.
Nice to see you.

800
00:46:10,040 --> 00:46:12,800
[Thomas]
Excuse me a second.

801
00:46:12,880 --> 00:46:14,720
- Hi.
- Hello.

802
00:46:14,800 --> 00:46:18,120
- How are you? Very nice
to meet you, Miss Celia Kirby.
- Good, thank you.

803
00:46:18,200 --> 00:46:21,480
It's a extremely beautiful name
for an extremely beautiful woman.

804
00:46:21,520 --> 00:46:23,600
Well, my, that was very smooth.

805
00:46:23,680 --> 00:46:25,920
You know, after about ten hours
straight on my feet,

806
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:28,400
making small talk, breathing in
that cheap cigar smoke,

807
00:46:28,480 --> 00:46:31,040
that is exactly the kind of line
I'm ready to fall for.

808
00:46:31,120 --> 00:46:34,280
- [Chuckling] Slow down, okay?
- Sure.

809
00:46:34,320 --> 00:46:37,360
Tell me, which one of these guys
is Congressman Johnson?

810
00:46:37,440 --> 00:46:39,320
- You're looking for the congressman?
- Yes.

811
00:46:39,400 --> 00:46:42,440
How would you feel if I told you
I was the congressman? Aha!

812
00:46:44,320 --> 00:46:45,920
- Oh, duh!
- I'm so sorry.

813
00:46:45,960 --> 00:46:48,560
Would you give me two seconds to take
my foot out of my mouth, please?

814
00:46:48,640 --> 00:46:52,080
Take all the time you need.
Can we start over again?

815
00:46:52,160 --> 00:46:54,400
Yes, Celia Kirby,
Legislative Director of Pro Bono.

816
00:46:54,440 --> 00:46:56,960
Celia kirby from Pro Bono!
Very nice to meet you.

817
00:46:57,000 --> 00:46:58,320
- Yes.
- Would you tell me something?

818
00:46:58,400 --> 00:47:00,560
Are all the pro bonettes
as fine as you?

819
00:47:00,640 --> 00:47:04,240
Pro Bono is a public interest
research and advocacy group.

820
00:47:04,320 --> 00:47:06,760
I'd be delighted to brief you
on our priorities this session.

821
00:47:06,840 --> 00:47:10,400
Do you think, perhaps, I could call
your A.A. and be put on your schedule?

822
00:47:10,480 --> 00:47:12,320
- Call my A.A.?
- Yes.

823
00:47:12,360 --> 00:47:15,480
No, you don't have to call my A.A.
Why don't we do this?

824
00:47:15,560 --> 00:47:18,760
Why don't we, say now, go out to
dinner? You can brief me at dinner.

825
00:47:18,840 --> 00:47:21,120
I'd like an appointment,
Congressman, not a date.

826
00:47:21,200 --> 00:47:23,240
We could write it up
as an appointment,

827
00:47:23,320 --> 00:47:25,280
but we'll have, like,
flowers and dinner,

828
00:47:25,360 --> 00:47:27,560
a mandolin, and it'll be
a "floral" appointment.

829
00:47:27,600 --> 00:47:31,240
It was a pleasure
to meet you, Congressman.
I will be in touch with your staff.

830
00:47:31,280 --> 00:47:34,160
There's one other thing.
I'm particularly interested...

831
00:47:34,240 --> 00:47:38,440
in hearing your view on extending
the sexual harassment law
to include congressmen.

832
00:47:38,520 --> 00:47:41,840
Oh. I get it.

833
00:47:41,920 --> 00:47:45,120
Can we turn the A.C. down, please?

834
00:47:51,520 --> 00:47:53,400
Thank you.

835
00:47:53,480 --> 00:47:57,640
Uh, I have a confession to make.
I don't know very much about poultry.

836
00:47:57,680 --> 00:47:59,600
But I do know people,

837
00:47:59,640 --> 00:48:02,600
and I like you people.
I really do.

838
00:48:02,680 --> 00:48:07,320
And if you people come to me
and you say to me...

839
00:48:07,400 --> 00:48:12,080
that you have something to say
important about poultry,

840
00:48:14,440 --> 00:48:17,760
I'm gonna listen.
Thank you very much.

841
00:48:34,800 --> 00:48:37,560
Thank you for seeing us.
We won't take up much of your time.

842
00:48:37,640 --> 00:48:39,480
- This is Ira Schecter,
our research director.
- Hi, Ira, how are you?

843
00:48:39,560 --> 00:48:41,480
This is Mr. Reinhardt.
You remember him?

844
00:48:41,560 --> 00:48:43,520
Come sit next to me
and have this chitchat.

845
00:48:43,600 --> 00:48:46,600
I've been dying to talk to you
about these issues.

846
00:48:46,680 --> 00:48:48,560
Sit, everybody, sit.
Come on.

847
00:48:48,600 --> 00:48:50,600
- All right.
- We can take as long as we want.

848
00:48:50,680 --> 00:48:52,560
Congressman, you do have
several people waiting.

849
00:48:52,600 --> 00:48:54,480
- No, no, they can wait.
- They can wait.

850
00:48:54,520 --> 00:48:57,520
What are you doing standing, Ira?
Sit down, Ira!

851
00:48:57,600 --> 00:48:59,440
Uh, sure.

852
00:48:59,520 --> 00:49:01,640
Well... [Clears Throat]
These are issue papers.

853
00:49:01,720 --> 00:49:03,760
- Ah.
- This session we're
targeting child safety,

854
00:49:03,840 --> 00:49:06,440
auto insurance premiums
and food additives.

855
00:49:06,520 --> 00:49:09,640
Certainly, as the votes come up, you'll
be hearing plenty from the other side.

856
00:49:09,680 --> 00:49:12,320
We simply would like a fair shot
at making our case too.

857
00:49:12,400 --> 00:49:14,600
- Absolutely.
- Absolutely.

858
00:49:14,640 --> 00:49:17,360
Okay, now, let's talk about car
insurance. What are you paying, Ira?

859
00:49:17,440 --> 00:49:19,520
- Me? Oh.
- [Thomas] Yes.

860
00:49:19,600 --> 00:49:23,560
Uh, well, I have an '82
Dodge Dart and, uh,

861
00:49:23,640 --> 00:49:28,000
I pay about $650 a year,
or so.

862
00:49:28,080 --> 00:49:30,360
Six hundred fifty dollars?
Man, that's highway robbery.

863
00:49:30,440 --> 00:49:34,440
A chop shop wouldn't give you more
than 230 on a junker like that.

864
00:49:34,480 --> 00:49:36,360
Or so I've heard.

865
00:49:37,560 --> 00:49:39,640
Hey, look,
I'm flying blind here.

866
00:49:39,720 --> 00:49:42,960
What we need to do is for you
to put together a little package.

867
00:49:43,040 --> 00:49:45,240
Put a package together
for me and we'll sit down.

868
00:49:45,320 --> 00:49:48,680
We'll block aside two Saturday evenings
and we can discuss it then.

869
00:49:48,760 --> 00:49:51,720
Well, I don't see any problem
with arranging that.

870
00:49:51,800 --> 00:49:54,800
Once again, you've been more than
generous with your time, Congressman.

871
00:49:54,880 --> 00:49:58,160
What are you doin'?
I clear my whole calendar and you're
in and outta here in five minutes?

872
00:49:58,240 --> 00:50:00,160
Look, sit down.
We haven't discussed child safety yet.

873
00:50:00,240 --> 00:50:03,720
Ira, sit. I'm gonna slap you.
Sit. Come on, down. Sit down!

874
00:50:03,760 --> 00:50:06,560
Let's finish talking.
Let's talk about child safety now.

875
00:50:06,600 --> 00:50:09,960
This is an important issue.
Child safety.

876
00:50:10,040 --> 00:50:13,920
Well, we are sponsoring a bill imposing
safety standards on imported toys.

877
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:16,240
Great. I hate imported toys.
Hate 'em.

878
00:50:16,320 --> 00:50:19,880
I wish they didn't exist.
Especially those little baseball men...

879
00:50:19,960 --> 00:50:22,800
with the springs in their neck that do
this. What is that? Fuck that, right?

880
00:50:22,880 --> 00:50:24,520
- Fuck that.
- [Thomas] Yeah, I hate that.

881
00:50:24,560 --> 00:50:26,880
Why don't we do this? Like I said,
put the package together.

882
00:50:26,960 --> 00:50:30,160
We'll block aside a couple of Saturday
evenings and we can discuss it...

883
00:50:30,240 --> 00:50:33,600
- And you can take me
through all the ins and outs.
- "Ins and outs"?

884
00:50:36,920 --> 00:50:38,800
I'd like to do
more money for you,

885
00:50:38,880 --> 00:50:41,120
but first I've got to get
your positions on a few issues.

886
00:50:41,200 --> 00:50:44,120
Now where are you
on sugar price supports?

887
00:50:45,320 --> 00:50:49,000
- Sugar price supports.
- Hmm?

888
00:50:49,040 --> 00:50:52,080
- Where should I be, Terry?
- Shit, it makes no difference to me.

889
00:50:52,160 --> 00:50:56,960
If you're for 'em, I got money
for you from my sugar producers
in Louisiana and Hawaii.

890
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:00,200
If you're against 'em, I got money
for you from the candy manufacturers.

891
00:51:02,680 --> 00:51:05,280
- You pick.
- Let's say... for.

892
00:51:05,360 --> 00:51:06,760
Yeah, for. For.

893
00:51:06,840 --> 00:51:10,760
How about putting limits
on malpractice awards?

894
00:51:13,880 --> 00:51:15,600
Oh, you tell me.

895
00:51:15,680 --> 00:51:18,800
If you're for 'em, I got money from
the doctors and insurance companies.

896
00:51:18,880 --> 00:51:22,320
If you're against 'em,
I got money from the trial lawyers.

897
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:28,040
- Let's put you down as against.
- Yeah, you know what?
Put me down for against.

898
00:51:29,120 --> 00:51:31,080
How about pizza?

899
00:51:31,120 --> 00:51:33,320
Oh, no, this salad
is gonna be enough for me.

900
00:51:33,360 --> 00:51:36,840
Not for lunch, old buddy.
For PAC money.

901
00:51:36,920 --> 00:51:40,000
You thought I was serious?
I was fuckin' with you.

902
00:51:40,040 --> 00:51:43,520
- Well, you are. You are!
- Fuckin' with you. Uh, duh!

903
00:51:43,560 --> 00:51:45,840
Terry, tell me something.

904
00:51:45,920 --> 00:51:49,000
With all this money
comin' in from both sides,

905
00:51:49,080 --> 00:51:51,200
how could anything
possibly ever get done?

906
00:51:51,240 --> 00:51:54,400
It doesn't.
That's the genius of the system.

907
00:51:54,480 --> 00:51:56,600
[Thomas, Terry Laugh]

908
00:51:56,680 --> 00:52:00,680
Hey, baby, put down nuclear
power for ten G's.

909
00:52:00,760 --> 00:52:02,600
Mambo!

910
00:52:02,680 --> 00:52:07,160
[Loretta]
Cool! Yeah, the congressman's
gonna be out your way next week.

911
00:52:07,240 --> 00:52:11,280
Mr. Willie? Congressman Johnson
calling. Can you take his call?

912
00:52:11,360 --> 00:52:14,240
Thank you. Please hold.

913
00:52:14,280 --> 00:52:16,240
A-one, a-two...

914
00:52:16,320 --> 00:52:19,240
Yes, Mr. Brown.
Uh-huh, on the 30th.

915
00:52:19,320 --> 00:52:21,240
We were wondering whether
you aerospace people...

916
00:52:21,320 --> 00:52:23,600
might want to lay on a luncheon
so that you can hear his views.

917
00:52:23,680 --> 00:52:27,560
I'm sorry, Mr. Willie.
He just picked up another call.

918
00:52:27,640 --> 00:52:31,680
I know why he was calling you. He hasn't
heard from you about his fund-raiser.

919
00:52:31,760 --> 00:52:35,520
A thousand dollars a head?
A whole table!

920
00:52:35,560 --> 00:52:38,640
Lovely. Yeah.

921
00:52:38,720 --> 00:52:42,040
Well, now, what kind of
a contribution to his foundation
were you folks thinking about?

922
00:52:47,800 --> 00:52:50,240
Now, we'll have a little
huntin' in the morning,

923
00:52:50,280 --> 00:52:52,280
little fishin' in the afternoon,

924
00:52:52,360 --> 00:52:54,840
clean air, beautiful scenery.

925
00:52:54,920 --> 00:52:57,840
All to work up a good appetite,
'cause we got a fine French chef...

926
00:52:57,920 --> 00:52:59,800
back at the lodge
flown in special.

927
00:52:59,880 --> 00:53:03,960
Oh! That's very, very nice.

928
00:53:04,040 --> 00:53:07,040
- You don't want anything from us?
- We would enjoy the opportunity...

929
00:53:07,120 --> 00:53:09,000
to share our views.

930
00:53:09,040 --> 00:53:12,640
You see, we feel that the semiautomatic
weapon's gotten a bad rap.

931
00:53:12,720 --> 00:53:16,280
Now, the gun control nuts try to make
out that they're for drug dealers only.

932
00:53:16,360 --> 00:53:20,520
But, uh, really, they're just guns
for the ordinary sportsman.

933
00:53:20,560 --> 00:53:24,360
[Chuckling]
Nothin' like a nice, warm Uzi.

934
00:53:24,400 --> 00:53:28,920
[Duck Call Quacking]

935
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:31,640
[Duck Call Continues]

936
00:53:36,920 --> 00:53:39,920
[Quacking]

937
00:53:54,600 --> 00:53:56,440
Yee-hee!

938
00:53:58,360 --> 00:54:01,240
Must have had a heart attack.

939
00:54:12,640 --> 00:54:14,320
Aaah!

940
00:54:16,640 --> 00:54:21,400
And according to the 1988 study,
it showed eight per 100,000.

941
00:54:23,760 --> 00:54:27,400
- Am I losing you on these
mortality rates, Congressman?
- No, not at all.

942
00:54:27,480 --> 00:54:32,120
I was, uh, I was just wondering
how much of this is a statutory problem,

943
00:54:32,200 --> 00:54:35,120
- And how much of it is a regulatory one.
- Mmm, mm-hmm.

944
00:54:35,200 --> 00:54:39,600
- Didn't the Merton Act
cover most of this?
- Excellent point.

945
00:54:39,680 --> 00:54:43,880
Excellent point.
Let me check something out.

946
00:54:43,920 --> 00:54:46,040
Excuse me.

947
00:54:50,440 --> 00:54:53,600
You're absolutely right.

948
00:54:53,640 --> 00:54:55,880
Maybe we could get them
to amend Merton.

949
00:54:55,960 --> 00:54:58,560
Oh, get 'em to amend it.

950
00:54:58,600 --> 00:55:00,520
Yes!

951
00:55:00,600 --> 00:55:04,520
Get 'em to amend it, huh?
Well, "For Merton to apply,

952
00:55:04,600 --> 00:55:08,120
you have to show high contagion.

953
00:55:08,200 --> 00:55:12,800
It sounds to me like
your contagion... rates...

954
00:55:12,840 --> 00:55:15,280
are no higher
than the common clod."

955
00:55:20,200 --> 00:55:22,960
"Cold." "Common cold."

956
00:55:23,040 --> 00:55:26,080
Excuse me a second. Arthur!

957
00:55:26,160 --> 00:55:29,600
- Ow!
- What were we talking about?

958
00:55:34,840 --> 00:55:38,640
How'd you wind up hustling for pro bono
instead of pesticides anyway?

959
00:55:38,720 --> 00:55:41,600
- 'Cause you could have
been a big-time lawyer.
- I was for a while.

960
00:55:41,640 --> 00:55:45,920
- But it depressed me.
- What could be depressing
about makin' $100,000 a year?

961
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:49,320
- I know you gotta get sick
of losin' all the time.
- Of course I do.

962
00:55:49,400 --> 00:55:52,400
Mainly it makes me angry,
and the anger keeps me going.

963
00:55:52,480 --> 00:55:56,040
Of course I'd like to win a few
and I'm not allergic to money either.

964
00:55:56,120 --> 00:55:59,040
- So why are you doin' it?
- Hey.

965
00:55:59,120 --> 00:56:03,360
It's so embarrassing to come
right out and say why I do it.

966
00:56:03,400 --> 00:56:06,240
- Why?
- It's embarrassing for me to say.

967
00:56:06,280 --> 00:56:08,280
- I just feel...
- Stop! What?

968
00:56:08,360 --> 00:56:11,320
Meaning!

969
00:56:11,400 --> 00:56:15,840
My life has to mean something.

970
00:56:15,880 --> 00:56:18,400
So now I have a question for you.

971
00:56:18,440 --> 00:56:22,200
I'd like to know how you
got named after a memorial.

972
00:56:22,280 --> 00:56:24,720
Oh.
[Chuckling]

973
00:56:24,800 --> 00:56:28,800
My grandmother liked Jefferson.
You know, "life, liberty
and the pursuit of happiness."

974
00:56:28,880 --> 00:56:31,040
You know,
old black folks' thing.

975
00:56:31,080 --> 00:56:35,800
There's a lot to live up to, so I
kinda specialize in one portion of that.

976
00:56:35,880 --> 00:56:38,440
That's the pursuit
of happiness.

977
00:56:38,480 --> 00:56:41,080
- And how's it going?
- Um.

978
00:56:41,160 --> 00:56:43,120
- Honestly?
- Mm-hmm.

979
00:56:43,200 --> 00:56:48,120
I was goin' real good
'til I met you.

980
00:56:48,200 --> 00:56:51,520
Now, the better I do,
the worse I feel.

981
00:56:51,600 --> 00:56:55,120
Isn't that strange?

982
00:57:03,440 --> 00:57:06,360
Mmm, when can I see you again?
Let's go to dinner Saturday night.

983
00:57:06,440 --> 00:57:11,080
- How about Sunday morning?
- Oh, oh, brunch?

984
00:57:11,160 --> 00:57:14,360
The wages of sin is death!

985
00:57:14,440 --> 00:57:19,680
And to the man who values
gold over goodness,

986
00:57:19,720 --> 00:57:22,680
the Lord allows no exemptions.

987
00:57:22,760 --> 00:57:26,600
- [Congregation] Amen.
- Amen.

988
00:57:26,680 --> 00:57:29,960
And to the man
who shows no respect...

989
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:33,080
for the privilege
of walking this Earth,

990
00:57:33,160 --> 00:57:36,040
the Lord allows no deductions.

991
00:57:36,120 --> 00:57:40,720
- Amen.
- And to the man whose
pockets are bulging...

992
00:57:40,800 --> 00:57:43,280
and whose soul is empty,

993
00:57:43,360 --> 00:57:47,080
the Lord grants
no 90-day extension.

994
00:57:48,720 --> 00:57:53,240
And when the last trump sounds,

995
00:57:53,320 --> 00:57:56,440
believe me,
you will be audited.

996
00:57:59,400 --> 00:58:04,000
This is a wonderful date.

997
00:58:05,080 --> 00:58:07,480
Oh, darling,
I'm glad you could make it!

998
00:58:07,560 --> 00:58:10,000
Oh, I love that sermon,
Uncle Eli.

999
00:58:10,080 --> 00:58:12,000
This is your uncle?

1000
00:58:12,040 --> 00:58:15,880
Yes, my niece tells me you're
not half as slimy as I thought.

1001
00:58:15,960 --> 00:58:19,960
That puts you somewhere between a lizard
and a toad. Quite a step up, huh?

1002
00:58:20,040 --> 00:58:21,880
Thank you very much.

1003
00:58:21,960 --> 00:58:24,120
Forgive me for staring. I don't know
how I missed the family resemblance.

1004
00:58:25,640 --> 00:58:29,400
She's you in a skirt.

1005
00:58:29,480 --> 00:58:31,680
[TV Announcer]... trailing by 13
as we begin the second half.

1006
00:58:31,720 --> 00:58:33,880
[Man] Yeah, I guess we're
all bringin' our wives.

1007
00:58:33,960 --> 00:58:36,440
Al, you gonna bring your wife,
ain't ya?

1008
00:58:36,520 --> 00:58:38,560
[Al Chuckling]
You bet.

1009
00:58:38,640 --> 00:58:41,200
[TV Continues Indistinct]

1010
00:58:41,280 --> 00:58:43,640
Uh-huh. Uh.

1011
00:58:43,720 --> 00:58:47,880
[TV Continues Indistinct]

1012
00:58:47,920 --> 00:58:49,840
Oh, I slipped.

1013
00:58:54,400 --> 00:58:56,840
- Ellie.
- How ya doin', Thomas?

1014
00:58:56,920 --> 00:58:59,080
I need your help
on the ethics bill, Leon.

1015
00:58:59,160 --> 00:59:02,920
- I want you to cosponsor my amendments.
- You make a persuasive case, Eli.

1016
00:59:02,960 --> 00:59:06,080
But that wasn't a yes.

1017
00:59:06,120 --> 00:59:09,560
I promise to give it
the attention it deserves.

1018
00:59:09,640 --> 00:59:13,120
- Better luck next time, son.
- Yeah, man, you're so good.
He's so good.

1019
00:59:13,200 --> 00:59:16,200
He took $600 off you
that last hand, didn't he?

1020
00:59:16,280 --> 00:59:18,320
- He took a real shinin' to me.
- If I didn't know any better,

1021
00:59:18,400 --> 00:59:20,560
I'd say you lost to him
on purpose.

1022
00:59:20,640 --> 00:59:22,720
There's nothin' wrong with lettin'
the head of the ethics committee...

1023
00:59:22,760 --> 00:59:24,640
roll ya every now and then.

1024
00:59:24,720 --> 00:59:28,200
You know, you're gonna fit in
real good around here. Too good.

1025
00:59:28,240 --> 00:59:30,760
How come you never ask me
to help you out with your amendments?

1026
00:59:30,840 --> 00:59:33,160
Oh, come on, Thomas.
Give it a rest.

1027
00:59:33,200 --> 00:59:35,640
Everybody knows
you're Dick Dodge's boy.

1028
00:59:35,720 --> 00:59:38,080
Hey, man, I ain't
nobody's boy, all right?

1029
00:59:38,120 --> 00:59:41,200
Don't waste your outrage on me.
I know what ya are.

1030
00:59:41,280 --> 00:59:46,280
- I am no different than
anybody else up here, okay?
- That's not true.

1031
00:59:46,320 --> 00:59:50,920
You see, some people here actually do
something besides saving their own ass.

1032
00:59:58,160 --> 01:00:02,160
You know, just then you
reminded me of my father.

1033
01:00:02,240 --> 01:00:06,600
Did I really? How so?

1034
01:00:06,680 --> 01:00:09,200
He used to say I was a scumbag too.

1035
01:00:09,280 --> 01:00:13,360
[Bell Ringing]

1036
01:00:13,440 --> 01:00:15,280
Aren't you going to vote?

1037
01:00:15,360 --> 01:00:18,880
Is that what that means?
You know, all this time I've
been listenin' to that shit,

1038
01:00:18,960 --> 01:00:21,800
thinkin' it was time for
Final Jeopardy or somethin'.

1039
01:00:36,360 --> 01:00:38,320
[Chuckling]

1040
01:00:38,480 --> 01:00:40,320
[Indistinct Chatter]

1041
01:00:40,400 --> 01:00:42,440
- [Thomas] Excuse me.
- Excuse me, Congressman.

1042
01:00:42,520 --> 01:00:45,080
- I'm Mrs. Koslowski.
- Hi, I'm leaving.

1043
01:00:45,160 --> 01:00:49,600
We were just learning how a bill
becomes a law. Was that a vote?

1044
01:00:49,640 --> 01:00:51,760
Yes, that was a vote in there.
Oh! Oh!

1045
01:00:51,840 --> 01:00:54,320
Yes, that was a vote.
A vote was made. Bye-bye.

1046
01:00:54,400 --> 01:00:58,640
- And what did you vote?
- Ah, I voted nay.

1047
01:00:58,680 --> 01:01:02,920
It was a terrible bill and it would have
destroyed the fabric of American life.

1048
01:01:02,960 --> 01:01:05,880
What was the vote on?

1049
01:01:05,960 --> 01:01:08,200
[Chuckling]
Rafe!

1050
01:01:08,280 --> 01:01:11,560
Rafe, will you talk to these nice
people. Explain to them about the vote.

1051
01:01:11,640 --> 01:01:14,640
Well, it was a motion on the
previous question on the rule.

1052
01:01:14,720 --> 01:01:17,920
No, it was a motion
on the recommitment...

1053
01:01:17,960 --> 01:01:21,600
of the rule of the motion
of the previous question.

1054
01:01:24,560 --> 01:01:26,680
- Which means?
- Clean air.

1055
01:01:26,760 --> 01:01:30,040
School lunches.

1056
01:01:32,840 --> 01:01:37,720
Ah, you see the difficult choices
we have to make here, kids,

1057
01:01:37,800 --> 01:01:41,960
between clean air
and school lunches, okay?

1058
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:44,520
That's why I want to be the education
congressman. See, 'cause I feel...

1059
01:01:44,600 --> 01:01:48,040
that American students should be able to
eat lunch and breathe at the same time.

1060
01:01:48,120 --> 01:01:50,880
And I see an America where
there's no such thing...

1061
01:01:50,920 --> 01:01:53,440
as a student
who is below average.

1062
01:01:53,520 --> 01:01:57,920
And I think it is wrong when students
have to stay up late at night...

1063
01:01:57,960 --> 01:02:00,080
and miss all the good shows
doing homework.

1064
01:02:00,160 --> 01:02:02,840
Then get up early in the mornin'
and go to school.

1065
01:02:02,920 --> 01:02:06,520
This sort of thing just is not fair.

1066
01:02:06,600 --> 01:02:11,160
[Cheering]

1067
01:02:13,640 --> 01:02:16,560
- Uh, good morning. May I help you?
- Yes, I'm Ellen Juba.

1068
01:02:16,640 --> 01:02:18,520
- This is my daughter, Mickey.
- Hi.

1069
01:02:18,600 --> 01:02:20,960
We'd like to see our congressman.
We live in the district.

1070
01:02:21,040 --> 01:02:23,600
Just a moment, please.

1071
01:02:23,680 --> 01:02:27,080
Ah, could you come out?
Thank you.

1072
01:02:27,160 --> 01:02:31,640
Be right with you.
I like your hat.

1073
01:02:35,360 --> 01:02:38,800
How do you do? I'm Miss Loretta,
public liaison for the congressman.

1074
01:02:38,880 --> 01:02:43,960
Ellen Juba, my daughter, Mickey.
We'd like to see him.

1075
01:02:44,040 --> 01:02:46,560
Y'all from the district?
Up here seeing the sights?

1076
01:02:46,600 --> 01:02:50,760
How'd you folks like some
gallery passes? Go listen
to the great debates of our day.

1077
01:02:50,800 --> 01:02:54,440
We don't wanna go to the gallery.
We wanna see Congressman Johnson.

1078
01:02:54,480 --> 01:02:58,000
Well, how about a house key ring?
For each of you?

1079
01:02:58,080 --> 01:03:02,560
Here, see that? Isn't that
something? Turns into a pen.

1080
01:03:02,600 --> 01:03:06,480
I don't think you understand.
We're not tourists. We're constituents.

1081
01:03:06,560 --> 01:03:10,320
You're not with some organization,
are you, honey?

1082
01:03:10,400 --> 01:03:12,680
I'm a goddamn citizen.
Isn't that enough?

1083
01:03:12,760 --> 01:03:15,200
Do you have an appointment?

1084
01:03:15,240 --> 01:03:19,320
No, I do not have
an appointment, because y'all
keep givin' me the runaround.

1085
01:03:19,400 --> 01:03:22,240
Well, I'm sorry, but the congressman
is a very busy man.

1086
01:03:22,280 --> 01:03:25,280
Now, if you'd like to discuss it
with me, I will personally...

1087
01:03:25,360 --> 01:03:28,240
go over the issue with him
and get a letter out to you.

1088
01:03:28,320 --> 01:03:31,560
We're not leaving here
until we see him.

1089
01:03:36,280 --> 01:03:39,480
Armando, would you come out front?
We have a situation.

1090
01:03:39,560 --> 01:03:42,840
You stop palming me off
on your flunkies.

1091
01:03:42,920 --> 01:03:45,120
Are you gonna go in there
and tell him we're out here...

1092
01:03:45,160 --> 01:03:47,080
or am I gonna go in there
and tell him myself?

1093
01:03:47,120 --> 01:03:49,000
- Excuse me, may I help you, please?
- Yes, you can.

1094
01:03:49,080 --> 01:03:51,840
- I would like to see
my congressman, please.
- He's not here today.

1095
01:03:51,920 --> 01:03:54,400
- I bet he is here. Excuse me.
- No, no, please, lady.

1096
01:03:54,480 --> 01:03:56,360
- No, you just let me by!
- No, don't push. Okay. Ya! Ya!

1097
01:03:56,400 --> 01:03:58,800
- [Indistinct Shouting]
- I am sick of this! I am fed up!

1098
01:03:58,880 --> 01:04:03,080
- I have every right! Let go of her!
- Hey!

1099
01:04:12,360 --> 01:04:14,840
Oh, baby.

1100
01:04:19,960 --> 01:04:22,480
Come on, Mama. Let's go.

1101
01:04:25,840 --> 01:04:27,760
Hey.

1102
01:04:30,880 --> 01:04:34,320
What happened to you?

1103
01:04:34,400 --> 01:04:37,320
The doctor says they got it all.
I'm gonna be okay.

1104
01:04:37,360 --> 01:04:40,000
I was lucky, but,
but there are others.

1105
01:04:40,040 --> 01:04:44,840
- What others?
- Other kids. They call it
a cancer cluster.

1106
01:04:44,920 --> 01:04:48,520
At first, none of us in the neighborhood
wanted to believe it.

1107
01:04:48,560 --> 01:04:50,440
But then we all saw it.

1108
01:04:50,480 --> 01:04:53,160
For me, it was when the two-year-old
across the street...

1109
01:04:53,240 --> 01:04:55,280
developed a brain tumor
same as Mickey's.

1110
01:04:55,360 --> 01:05:00,320
We looked at everything:
the water, the air, dump sites.

1111
01:05:00,400 --> 01:05:03,280
Insects, you name it.

1112
01:05:03,360 --> 01:05:06,840
And then we realized it was
starin' us right in the face.

1113
01:05:06,920 --> 01:05:10,280
- What?
- Power lines.

1114
01:05:10,360 --> 01:05:12,280
High-voltage power lines.

1115
01:05:12,360 --> 01:05:17,080
The wires cause magnetic fields
and the magnetic fields cause cancer,

1116
01:05:17,160 --> 01:05:19,040
especially in children.

1117
01:05:19,080 --> 01:05:21,600
I've never heard anything
like that in my life.

1118
01:05:21,680 --> 01:05:24,680
Why don't you just
come see for yourself?

1119
01:05:24,760 --> 01:05:26,960
[Children Laughing]

1120
01:05:36,880 --> 01:05:41,320
- This is Mickey's school?
- Uh-huh.

1121
01:05:41,400 --> 01:05:44,680
It turns out a lot of schools
are near power lines.

1122
01:05:44,760 --> 01:05:48,640
Land's cheap, so schools tend
to buy it from the power companies.

1123
01:05:48,720 --> 01:05:53,000
We're nobody, Congressman.
You're somebody.

1124
01:05:53,080 --> 01:05:57,800
- We need your help.
- [Sighing]

1125
01:05:57,840 --> 01:06:01,000
Will you excuse me
for a second? Come here.

1126
01:06:05,160 --> 01:06:08,280
- Is this real?
- That depends on who you ask.

1127
01:06:08,360 --> 01:06:11,640
Some people say it's worse
than asbestos or breast implants.

1128
01:06:11,720 --> 01:06:13,560
Others say it's coincidental.

1129
01:06:13,640 --> 01:06:15,520
Well, you. What do you say?

1130
01:06:15,560 --> 01:06:18,760
I think it's very suspicious that the
White House would kill an EPA report...

1131
01:06:18,840 --> 01:06:21,480
saying that power lines
probably cause cancer.

1132
01:06:21,520 --> 01:06:24,480
- They did that?
- Yes.

1133
01:06:26,800 --> 01:06:29,480
[Sighing]

1134
01:06:29,520 --> 01:06:31,840
Well, I gotta do somethin'
to help these people.

1135
01:06:31,880 --> 01:06:34,320
Don't tell me you're actually
developing a conscience.

1136
01:06:34,400 --> 01:06:37,520
Oh, God, I hope not. It'd be
a fuckin' nuisance in Congress.

1137
01:06:37,600 --> 01:06:39,560
But if I were,
what could I do to help them?

1138
01:06:39,640 --> 01:06:41,600
This goes beyond personal tragedy.

1139
01:06:41,680 --> 01:06:46,040
It goes to a public health hazard
of unknown proportions.

1140
01:06:46,120 --> 01:06:49,400
It goes to the right of the ordinary
people to know all the facts!

1141
01:06:49,480 --> 01:06:51,920
Yeah, people ought to know if
the neighborhoods are killing them.

1142
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:54,400
Amen, gentlemen.

1143
01:06:54,440 --> 01:06:58,080
Amen! And what a fine effort it is.
I'm totally sympathetic.

1144
01:06:58,120 --> 01:07:01,080
Congressional hearings should
be scheduled just as soon as possible.

1145
01:07:01,160 --> 01:07:04,040
The American people
deserve no less.

1146
01:07:04,120 --> 01:07:07,880
Message: we care.

1147
01:07:07,920 --> 01:07:09,720
Turn this way, please.

1148
01:07:09,800 --> 01:07:12,040
- Right here, sir. Great!
- Over here.

1149
01:07:12,120 --> 01:07:15,120
[Thundering]

1150
01:07:15,200 --> 01:07:19,200
Cheers.

1151
01:07:19,280 --> 01:07:21,520
You know, son,
you're a real comer.

1152
01:07:21,600 --> 01:07:25,160
I wouldn't be a bit surprised
if you ended up in the leadership.

1153
01:07:25,200 --> 01:07:27,520
I'll say this,
if I were speaker,

1154
01:07:27,560 --> 01:07:29,600
I'd sleep better with you
as a lieutenant.

1155
01:07:29,680 --> 01:07:32,920
Thank you very much, Mr. Chairman.
I'm surprised to hear you say that.

1156
01:07:33,000 --> 01:07:35,840
'Cause I really honestly didn't
think you was gonna go with me
on this power lines thing.

1157
01:07:35,920 --> 01:07:39,760
- But I'm not.
- But you said you're sympathetic.

1158
01:07:39,840 --> 01:07:43,840
Well, of course I did. We're all
sympathetic to little girls with cancer.

1159
01:07:43,920 --> 01:07:47,200
But I'm not sympathetic
to holding a public inquiry.

1160
01:07:47,240 --> 01:07:50,440
- You just said...
- I know what I said.

1161
01:07:50,480 --> 01:07:52,800
But sound bites
aren't sworn testimony.

1162
01:07:52,840 --> 01:07:57,600
Now look, son, it's great to get
your name in the newspaper.

1163
01:07:57,680 --> 01:08:00,760
Let 'em know you care.
Very smart move, Thomas.

1164
01:08:00,840 --> 01:08:04,120
But that's as far as I
would go with this if I were you.

1165
01:08:04,200 --> 01:08:07,120
[Intercom Buzzing]

1166
01:08:08,920 --> 01:08:11,560
Yeah? Oh, fine, fine.

1167
01:08:11,640 --> 01:08:14,160
No, no, no, send 'em in.

1168
01:08:14,240 --> 01:08:16,320
We've got some
unexpected visitors.

1169
01:08:16,360 --> 01:08:18,760
- Hope you don't mind.
- Oh, hell, no.

1170
01:08:18,800 --> 01:08:21,000
Sure, great.

1171
01:08:21,080 --> 01:08:24,000
[Laughing]
Mr. Chairman!

1172
01:08:24,040 --> 01:08:25,960
Olaf!

1173
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:29,600
- Hello, Terry.
- Evenin', Mr. Chairman.

1174
01:08:29,680 --> 01:08:32,720
Thanks for tak...
Thomas!

1175
01:08:32,800 --> 01:08:35,880
They let you in here,
you S.O.B.?

1176
01:08:35,960 --> 01:08:38,880
You folks finally gonna
get to press flesh. Olaf!

1177
01:08:38,960 --> 01:08:42,880
Come and meet Thomas Johnson.
Thomas, Olaf Andersen.

1178
01:08:42,960 --> 01:08:45,240
- Chairman, Gulf Coast Power.
- Glad to meet ya, son.

1179
01:08:45,320 --> 01:08:47,600
They tell me you got
a real talent for the game.

1180
01:08:47,680 --> 01:08:52,360
This is Zeke Bridges, CEO,
Superior Mutual Insurance.

1181
01:08:55,280 --> 01:08:58,560
Som-bitch.

1182
01:08:58,640 --> 01:09:02,280
- Oh, you two know each other?
- Ah, no, we haven't met.

1183
01:09:02,320 --> 01:09:04,320
But I know a great deal
about the man.

1184
01:09:04,400 --> 01:09:06,600
We share a common interest
in international affairs.

1185
01:09:06,640 --> 01:09:09,000
Swedish in particular.

1186
01:09:10,840 --> 01:09:15,240
Oh, another Rolex. I collect these.
Mine's a slightly older model.

1187
01:09:15,280 --> 01:09:17,280
Can I have a double bourbon,
please?

1188
01:09:17,360 --> 01:09:19,880
It is very nice finally
meeting you, Mr. Bridges.

1189
01:09:19,920 --> 01:09:22,960
Yes, it's nice to meet you,
Congressman.

1190
01:09:23,040 --> 01:09:28,040
Thomas and I were just talkin'
about, uh, power lines.

1191
01:09:28,120 --> 01:09:30,880
Man, I think we oughta
have those hearings.

1192
01:09:30,960 --> 01:09:35,080
Well, now look, Thomas, why don't
we get, uh, Olaf's take on this?

1193
01:09:35,120 --> 01:09:37,920
Well, it's tragic.
Cancer's a terrible thing.

1194
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:39,920
But there's no way you
can link it to power lines.

1195
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:42,880
- The truth is...
- Wait a minute,
there have been studies...

1196
01:09:42,920 --> 01:09:47,000
Every study that says one thing,
I'll show you a study saying another.

1197
01:09:47,080 --> 01:09:49,800
We've studied this ourselves.
Nada.

1198
01:09:49,880 --> 01:09:51,880
What if all you guys
are wrong?

1199
01:09:51,960 --> 01:09:54,640
Thomas, do you want us
to move the power lines?

1200
01:09:54,720 --> 01:09:57,520
You know how much it would cost to bury
those things in Florida alone?

1201
01:09:57,600 --> 01:10:01,920
- We're talkin' $5 billion.
- Not counting the liability claims.

1202
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:05,480
How would you like
the people in your district
to think of you as the fellow...

1203
01:10:05,560 --> 01:10:08,360
who tripled
their electric bill?

1204
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:14,280
I just thought that if
we had the hearings...

1205
01:10:14,360 --> 01:10:16,480
Think for a moment, chum.
You hold your hearings.

1206
01:10:16,560 --> 01:10:19,080
Overnight, everyone who
lives near a substation...

1207
01:10:19,160 --> 01:10:21,920
will find the value
of his home in the toilet.

1208
01:10:22,000 --> 01:10:25,760
- You'll kill the real estate market.
- You'll kill the insurance companies.

1209
01:10:25,800 --> 01:10:28,880
- You'll kill the school district.
- You'll kill the local economy.

1210
01:10:28,960 --> 01:10:31,960
[Thundering]

1211
01:10:35,080 --> 01:10:38,240
Son, system ain't perfect.

1212
01:10:38,280 --> 01:10:40,800
But the fleas come with the dog.

1213
01:10:44,240 --> 01:10:47,080
Maybe I should
think about it, huh?

1214
01:10:47,120 --> 01:10:49,080
- Atta boy.
- [Clearing Throat]

1215
01:10:49,160 --> 01:10:52,680
Oh, Thomas, on a completely
different subject here.

1216
01:10:52,720 --> 01:10:54,920
You haven't set up
a state PAC yet, have ya?

1217
01:10:55,000 --> 01:10:58,760
'Cause I'd be happy to start one off
with a contribution of, say, 200,000.

1218
01:11:02,880 --> 01:11:04,720
No strings attached.

1219
01:11:04,800 --> 01:11:08,280
Natch.

1220
01:11:14,960 --> 01:11:17,000
- You were beautiful, Olaf.
- No, you were beautiful, Dick.

1221
01:11:17,080 --> 01:11:21,520
- No, you were beautiful, Terry.
- To the mutual aid society.

1222
01:11:40,120 --> 01:11:42,560
- Hey.
- Hi.

1223
01:11:42,640 --> 01:11:46,640
So? Are the Jubas
gonna testify? Hmm?

1224
01:11:46,720 --> 01:11:48,640
When's the committee
holding hearings?

1225
01:11:48,720 --> 01:11:53,360
Um, actually, I think the, the hearings
might be postponed a little bit.

1226
01:11:53,440 --> 01:11:55,360
What's Dodge pulling now?

1227
01:11:55,440 --> 01:11:59,920
Nothin'. It's actually kinda good,
'cause now I get to, you know...

1228
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:03,840
Get to round up some other members
and get my ducks in a row and...

1229
01:12:07,280 --> 01:12:09,720
[Laughing]

1230
01:12:09,800 --> 01:12:12,480
- You shafted me on the ethics bill!
- Hey, Eli!

1231
01:12:12,520 --> 01:12:16,000
You just missed a good one.
Wait a minute, that reminds me.

1232
01:12:16,040 --> 01:12:19,360
- Same two old men on a park bench...
- It's a closed rule!

1233
01:12:19,400 --> 01:12:22,280
I can't get my amendments on the floor!
I can't get a recorded vote.

1234
01:12:22,320 --> 01:12:24,240
I can't get squat!

1235
01:12:24,280 --> 01:12:26,960
This is not the rules committee.
This is the steam room.

1236
01:12:27,040 --> 01:12:30,920
This is the U.S. Congress. The American
people deserve better than this!

1237
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:34,560
You know what your problem is, Eli?
You've got "sermonitis."

1238
01:12:34,640 --> 01:12:35,880
[Laughing]

1239
01:12:35,920 --> 01:12:39,560
Now, why don't you just relax?
Have a massage.

1240
01:12:39,600 --> 01:12:44,840
I've got news for ya, Dick.
I'm gonna run against you for speaker.

1241
01:12:44,880 --> 01:12:47,360
I'm gonna make this
whole race boil down...

1242
01:12:47,400 --> 01:12:50,160
to whether we want a sleaze like you
in the speaker's chair.

1243
01:12:50,240 --> 01:12:53,760
I'll bet ya $100
you don't get ten votes.

1244
01:12:53,800 --> 01:12:56,680
[Sighing]
I'm gonna be your shadow, Dick.

1245
01:12:56,720 --> 01:13:00,400
Every member ya strong-arm,
every reporter ya background,

1246
01:13:00,480 --> 01:13:03,640
every talk show ya go on,
I'll be there.

1247
01:13:03,720 --> 01:13:06,440
Five votes!
Nobody likes to hear a sermon.

1248
01:13:06,480 --> 01:13:10,080
I may not have a rat's ass
of a chance to beat you,

1249
01:13:10,120 --> 01:13:12,480
but I sure as hell
can let the world know...

1250
01:13:12,520 --> 01:13:15,360
what you stand for.

1251
01:13:23,560 --> 01:13:26,040
I went too far with him.
I know it.

1252
01:13:26,120 --> 01:13:28,960
- Now you know him
pretty well, don't you?
- I wouldn't say I knew him well.

1253
01:13:29,040 --> 01:13:32,080
Oh, come on, Thomas,
you're seein' his niece.

1254
01:13:32,160 --> 01:13:35,200
- Hell, you've been out
to his damn church.
- How do you know that?

1255
01:13:35,280 --> 01:13:38,120
Because I keep my ear
to the ground.

1256
01:13:38,160 --> 01:13:40,400
Now, Thomas,
he'll listen to you.

1257
01:13:40,480 --> 01:13:42,880
I want you to go make
the peace between us.

1258
01:13:42,960 --> 01:13:45,320
Tell him we'll work something out
with his amendments.

1259
01:13:45,360 --> 01:13:49,640
Not a vote, I won't go that far.
But at least he'll get to say
his peace from the floor.

1260
01:13:49,720 --> 01:13:51,760
Just get him off of my back.

1261
01:13:55,800 --> 01:13:58,160
- Another round?
- Yeah, why not?

1262
01:13:58,240 --> 01:14:01,240
To the honorable Dick Dodge.

1263
01:14:02,920 --> 01:14:04,800
Hey.

1264
01:14:06,840 --> 01:14:09,800
By the time I'm finished with him,
he won't be speaker.

1265
01:14:09,880 --> 01:14:11,880
He'll be lucky
if they don't indict him.

1266
01:14:11,960 --> 01:14:15,720
Eli, people do things that they regret,
man. People make mistakes.

1267
01:14:15,800 --> 01:14:18,120
- Dick's been under
a lot of pressure lately.
- Come on!

1268
01:14:18,160 --> 01:14:20,280
Thomas, you're
Dick Dodge's yes-man.

1269
01:14:20,360 --> 01:14:23,840
I am not a yes-man.
When Dick says no, I say no.

1270
01:14:23,880 --> 01:14:27,840
I know what you're up to.
He's scared and this is damage control.

1271
01:14:27,880 --> 01:14:32,560
Yeah, well, you know what?
This town...

1272
01:14:32,640 --> 01:14:35,320
It isn't about
passin' laws anymore.

1273
01:14:35,400 --> 01:14:38,720
It isn't about
doing good anymore.

1274
01:14:38,800 --> 01:14:42,400
All it's about...
is bein' here.

1275
01:14:42,440 --> 01:14:45,680
[Loretta]
Well, as I live and breathe.

1276
01:14:45,760 --> 01:14:48,040
- Hey, cuz.
- Hey.

1277
01:14:48,080 --> 01:14:51,960
Oh, I'm sorry. This is
Miss Loretta Hicks from my staff.

1278
01:14:52,040 --> 01:14:54,480
- This is Congressman Hawkins.
- Pleasure to meet you.

1279
01:14:54,560 --> 01:14:58,080
Oh, would you like a drink?

1280
01:14:58,120 --> 01:15:01,560
You know, you two look like you
could use a designated driver.

1281
01:15:01,640 --> 01:15:05,200
- Oh, good samaritan.
- Praise 'em.

1282
01:15:10,560 --> 01:15:13,920
[Dispatcher] Number 22,
I got a pickup at the Regency,

1283
01:15:13,960 --> 01:15:16,080
going to National.

1284
01:15:19,040 --> 01:15:21,480
You want a girlfriend?

1285
01:15:21,560 --> 01:15:24,880
[Dispatcher]
Eighteen, Union Station.

1286
01:15:36,080 --> 01:15:38,840
Shit!

1287
01:15:38,920 --> 01:15:42,600
[Indistinct Yelling]

1288
01:15:42,680 --> 01:15:46,440
[Indistinct]

1289
01:15:56,360 --> 01:15:58,200
Oh, shit.

1290
01:16:18,960 --> 01:16:20,880
Yeah, I need
an ambulance right away.

1291
01:16:23,080 --> 01:16:26,000
[Telephone Beeping]
Hello?

1292
01:16:26,080 --> 01:16:28,280
- It's somebody called Thomas Johnson.
- Oh.

1293
01:16:28,360 --> 01:16:30,600
- What's wrong?
- I went out with Hawkins.

1294
01:16:30,680 --> 01:16:33,480
We got in an accident.
He's out cold. I'm okay though.

1295
01:16:33,520 --> 01:16:38,120
- Were you driving?
- No, it was Miss Loretta.

1296
01:16:38,200 --> 01:16:41,400
- The girl from your office?
- Yeah. Hey, look, man.

1297
01:16:41,480 --> 01:16:43,520
I don't like the way
this looks for anybody, okay?

1298
01:16:43,600 --> 01:16:46,480
You said you wanted to
get back in Hawkins' good graces.
This is your opportunity.

1299
01:16:46,560 --> 01:16:50,800
All right. Now you listen
to me very carefully.

1300
01:16:50,880 --> 01:16:53,520
I want you to tell the ambulance
to take you to Walter Reed Hospital.

1301
01:16:53,600 --> 01:16:57,160
It's a privilege they extend
to congressmen. They'll keep it quiet.

1302
01:16:57,240 --> 01:17:01,640
I'll handle the police and you go home.
Keep your mouth shut.

1303
01:17:01,720 --> 01:17:03,760
[Beeping]

1304
01:17:03,840 --> 01:17:07,040
- [Ringing]
- What? What? What?

1305
01:17:08,600 --> 01:17:12,520
Hello? Hello?
Mr... . Mr... . Mr. Chairman?

1306
01:17:12,600 --> 01:17:16,000
Um, um, um,
no, no, no, no, sir.

1307
01:17:16,080 --> 01:17:18,560
No, no, I'm,
I'm, I'm a night owl.

1308
01:17:18,640 --> 01:17:22,200
Uh-huh, um...

1309
01:17:22,280 --> 01:17:24,520
Oh, my God,
is, is he all right?

1310
01:17:26,200 --> 01:17:29,480
G-Good, good, good.
Um, and, and Eli and Loretta?

1311
01:17:30,560 --> 01:17:35,400
Uh-huh, uh-huh.

1312
01:17:35,440 --> 01:17:38,040
Uh-huh.

1313
01:17:38,120 --> 01:17:39,960
That's brilliant,
Mr. Chairman.

1314
01:17:40,040 --> 01:17:44,000
No, I'll call the morning shows and
leak the information. They'll eat it up.

1315
01:17:44,080 --> 01:17:47,520
At the top of the news,
Maryland Congressman Elijah Hawkins...

1316
01:17:47,560 --> 01:17:50,600
is in satisfactory condition
at Walter Reed Hospital...

1317
01:17:50,680 --> 01:17:52,640
after an overnight accident
in the district.

1318
01:17:52,720 --> 01:17:57,040
That's right, Laura. Hawkins
reportedly had alcohol in his blood.

1319
01:17:57,120 --> 01:18:00,400
Also slightly injured was
an unidentified woman whom police say...

1320
01:18:00,480 --> 01:18:02,640
is linked to a phone-sex
operation in Florida.

1321
01:18:02,720 --> 01:18:04,680
- Shit.
- Linda, Congressman Hawkins?

1322
01:18:04,760 --> 01:18:07,080
That's Reverend Hawkins,
isn't it?

1323
01:18:07,160 --> 01:18:10,440
Right you are, Laura. And how this plays
into his longstanding campaign...

1324
01:18:10,480 --> 01:18:12,920
to reform congressional ethics
is now anyone's guess.

1325
01:18:14,640 --> 01:18:16,520
I'm trying to find
Reverend Eli Hawkins.

1326
01:18:16,560 --> 01:18:20,640
[Nurse]
Let me check for you.

1327
01:18:20,720 --> 01:18:23,680
Yes, he's right around
the corner there.

1328
01:18:26,160 --> 01:18:29,160
Stay away from him.
Stay away from me too.

1329
01:18:29,240 --> 01:18:32,160
- Celia, listen, we were set up.
- We were set up?

1330
01:18:32,240 --> 01:18:34,600
You were in the car. I didn't hear
your name mentioned on the news.

1331
01:18:34,640 --> 01:18:38,800
- Somethin' stinks here.
- It sure does,
and guess who it is, Thomas?

1332
01:18:38,880 --> 01:18:40,760
You don't give a damn
about anything, do you?

1333
01:18:40,840 --> 01:18:42,720
To think the other night
I actually thought you cared...

1334
01:18:42,800 --> 01:18:45,440
- About somebody other than yourself.
- You know how I feel about...

1335
01:18:45,480 --> 01:18:48,640
Not me! You jerk!
Mickey Juba.

1336
01:18:48,680 --> 01:18:51,920
You caved on the power lines,
didn't you?

1337
01:18:52,000 --> 01:18:55,720
Don't even answer because I know
you did. What'd you get for it?

1338
01:18:55,800 --> 01:18:58,760
- Are you gonna let me talk?
- Get the hell outta here.

1339
01:18:58,800 --> 01:19:01,640
Get out!

1340
01:19:10,280 --> 01:19:13,400
[Thomas]
Hattie! Hattie Rifkin?

